title: Should the NuCypher and Keep networks pursue a collaboration?
body:
__Background__
The NuCypher and Keep communities recently proposed an on-chain collaboration that would form a unified threshold cryptography network. The original proposals and subsequent community discussion can be found in the links below:
 * NuCypher DAO forum: https://dao.nucypher.com/t/codename-keanu-the-first-ever-decentralized-on-chain-network-hard-merge-between-keep-and-nucypher/159
* Keep forum: https://forum.keep.network/t/proposal-keep-and-nucypher-hard-merge/74
 
Based on initial feedback there appears to be sufficient support in both communities to continue working towards this collaboration and iterate on a final proposal.

__Signal__
This informal signal is meant to gauge continuing Staker support for the above. It is not a formal DAO proposal and it has no on-chain impact.

It’s meant purely as an opportunity for Stakers to signal their interest or non-interest in a future final proposal that would capture the following key terms: 

* A new staking contract that would accept either NU or KEEP, with an approximate 50/50 split in staking power (likely weighted by the stake-able supply in each network)
* Creation of a DAO for the new network controlled by Stakers
* Launch of tBTC v2 on this new network, with the ability for existing NU stakers to opt-in and earn fees

__Next Steps__
If there is sufficient Staker support for this signal, then the communities would continue to collaborate on developing a final proposal for DAO approval.

A final proposal would address implementation details, economic design, and other relevant considerations, which would be the subject of forthcoming community discussions and signals.

For example, a significant economic consideration would be the percentage of unminted NU supply transferred to the control of the unified network’s DAO.
